00:58:04,785 --> 00:58:12,070
[SPEAKER_00]: But I just a clarifying point that it became apparent to us as we saw some of the communications that were.

527
00:58:12,760 --> 00:58:28,112
[SPEAKER_00]: circulating around the district is that all substantive proposals for any type of reforms that the district was prioritizing, we communicated as early as last spring a willingness to withdraw those proposals.

528
00:58:28,672 --> 00:58:37,179
[SPEAKER_00]: And so it is not the case that all parties received exactly what they want based on their initial proposals.

529
00:58:37,679 --> 00:58:41,342
[SPEAKER_00]: And there are a couple of issues that the union has prioritized that

530
00:58:41,722 --> 00:58:54,133
[SPEAKER_00]: while the district did engage and made counter proposals on, we've reached a point where we don't necessarily believe at this point that there's room in this negotiation to change the current contractual language on.

531
00:58:54,833 --> 00:59:05,142
[SPEAKER_00]: All of those issues, and particularly the ones that the elementary prep time that I know has been spoken frequently about publicly in this forum, that issue has been withdrawn.

532
00:59:05,962 --> 00:59:08,765
[SPEAKER_00]: As far as the district's concerned, it's no longer being negotiated.

533
00:59:09,245 --> 00:59:23,376
[SPEAKER_00]: And so I recognize that there are some qualifiers there, but if you see that last bullet point, from the district's perspective, and I can only speak from the district's perspective, this negotiation, the scope of this negotiation is now narrowed.

534
00:59:23,871 --> 00:59:24,791
[SPEAKER_00]: to financial issues.

535
00:59:25,272 --> 00:59:38,958
[SPEAKER_00]: And those financial issues, for some of the reasons that we're going to talk about tonight, and I think the ones that are for reasons that are very clear, particularly to the people whose income is being affected by those issues, those are very serious issues, and they're very real issues.

536
00:59:39,538 --> 00:59:48,782
[SPEAKER_00]: And no matter how steadfast our disagreement might be with respect to what's responsible budgeting and what's responsible negotiating,

537
00:59:49,482 --> 00:59:57,288
[SPEAKER_00]: I don't want to do anything to suggest that we diminish the consequence or the impact of what we're negotiating.

538
00:59:57,328 --> 01:00:00,791
[SPEAKER_00]: And certainly, for some of our other bargaining units, as Ms.

539
01:00:00,831 --> 01:00:10,818
[SPEAKER_00]: Coppola just shared with us, it's both a real impact on our employees, and it's a real impact on our ability to function as an organization.

540
01:00:13,083 --> 01:00:27,895
[SPEAKER_00]: With that said, I do need to walk through the proposals that have been exchanged because I don't believe that we can have appropriate context for where we are now without understanding how these negotiations have progressed.

541
01:00:28,476 --> 01:00:37,984
[SPEAKER_00]: And I will say just as we go to the next slide, if I had to identify an objective for this presentation tonight, it is definitely not

542
01:00:38,604 --> 01:00:47,286
[SPEAKER_00]: for everyone to agree that what the district is offering is good and is fair, and that everyone should just come to the table and sign on the dotted line.

543
01:00:47,346 --> 01:00:56,549
[SPEAKER_00]: That's not the point of the message that the district has been circulating over the course of the last week since the declaration of the impasse, and it's not my objective tonight.

544
01:00:57,509 --> 01:01:05,631
[SPEAKER_00]: However, I do believe that in looking at what the district has proposed in the context in which we've proposed it,

545
01:01:06,539 --> 01:01:11,361
[SPEAKER_00]: It is unreasonable to say that these proposals are inherently disrespectful.

546
01:01:12,081 --> 01:01:15,182
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think it is even more problematic to say that that is their intent.

547
01:01:15,862 --> 01:01:24,805
[SPEAKER_00]: Because for those of us who do this side of the work, which if you haven't pieced together is not necessarily the most enjoyable part of the work.

548
01:01:27,366 --> 01:01:42,355
[SPEAKER_00]: The idea that we would do this with some type of latent intent or explicit intent to disrespect people or to not treat them with the dignity that we think educators should be afforded is far removed from reality.

549
01:01:42,896 --> 01:01:49,460
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think that the employees of the organization and the members of the Medford community have a

550
01:01:50,240 --> 01:01:54,582
[SPEAKER_00]: a right to know where the district administration stands.

551
01:01:55,162 --> 01:02:11,208
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think they, at this point, have a right to hear directly from us, which is why we're presenting this to you and why we're soliciting the support of a mediator to try to move this forward so we can mercifully move on from this topic and start focusing on the actual work of the Medford Public Schools.

552
01:02:12,148 --> 01:02:18,613
[SPEAKER_00]: The union's initial wage proposal was for a 6% increase per year, 18% over three years.

553
01:02:19,114 --> 01:02:25,098
[SPEAKER_00]: There were other compensation components to that, but that was certainly the centerpiece of that.

554
01:02:25,499 --> 01:02:29,482
[SPEAKER_00]: The rationale provided and has been provided publicly so that I'm not

555
01:02:29,922 --> 01:02:45,607
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm not speaking on their behalf, and they can certainly do that on their own, was due to the pronounced inflation that is affecting the country as well as the Medford area, as well as the significant hardship that all educators have endured during the COVID disruption.

556
01:02:46,607 --> 01:02:52,748
[SPEAKER_00]: I'll touch upon both of those points, the inflation argument as well as the COVID argument momentarily.

557
01:02:53,769 --> 01:03:14,513
[SPEAKER_00]: But before we get to that, I need to say publicly what I've communicated to the union, which is that a school district in Massachusetts with a 2.5% cap on the aggregate income property taxes and the revenue that can be raised cannot afford anything close to 18% over three years.

558
01:03:16,215 --> 01:03:24,885
[SPEAKER_00]: I to be clear, this is an initial proposal and I don't I don't believe that anyone felt that they were going to receive an 18% increase over three years.

559
01:03:26,267 --> 01:03:32,194
[SPEAKER_00]: However, because of that proposal that was made in January, the district was faced with two choices.

560
01:03:33,376 --> 01:03:44,232
[SPEAKER_00]: we could make a proposal that was very, very low to give us the room to negotiate, to get into the vicinity of where we knew we could sustain based on our budget.

561
01:03:44,732 --> 01:03:49,740
[SPEAKER_00]: But by giving that low proposal, it was inevitable that it would seem disrespectful.

562
01:03:51,493 --> 01:04:09,424
[SPEAKER_00]: The second choice was to make a proposal that was in the vicinity of what we could responsibly afford, and then be in a position where we were boxed in and could only make minuscule or incremental movement from the point of that proposal, and then be accused of being disrespectful because our movement was so slow.

563
01:04:10,084 --> 01:04:14,647
[SPEAKER_00]: This was communicated multiple times in multiple forms.

564
01:04:15,800 --> 01:04:21,302
[SPEAKER_00]: After two months, the district made a wage proposal in the hope of moving the discourse forward.

565
01:04:22,163 --> 01:04:32,067
[SPEAKER_00]: That proposal was 2%, one and three quarters percent, one and a half, which as I said, is very low.

566
01:04:33,427 --> 01:04:40,150
[SPEAKER_00]: But on March 29th, which I believe was the date that we made that proposal, and perhaps March 27th, it was the last week of March,

567
01:04:41,149 --> 01:04:45,571
[SPEAKER_00]: we felt at that point that that was our only option to try to move the conversation forward.

568
01:04:47,071 --> 01:05:01,456
[SPEAKER_00]: We also, in that proposal and in every compensation proposal since, offered to use the grant funding that was available to us to supplement that pay, provided that that supplement was not incorporated into the base pay.

569
01:05:02,776 --> 01:05:07,458
[SPEAKER_00]: That's been the district's position from the very beginning, that while the grant funding is temporary,

570
01:05:08,655 --> 01:05:10,665
[SPEAKER_00]: and will not exist in a short period of time.

571
01:05:11,564 --> 01:05:24,669
[SPEAKER_00]: given our prioritization of valuing our staff, respecting our staff, and recognizing the difficulty that our staff has gone through, particularly over the last couple of years, that it is an appropriate use of that funding.

572
01:05:25,129 --> 01:05:36,934
[SPEAKER_00]: There are some logistical hurdles, frankly, to using that money, and that's something that we've tried to work through, and we've tried to be as transparent as possible with respect to those proposals.

573
01:05:37,634 --> 01:05:39,535
[SPEAKER_00]: From the time that we made that proposal,

574
01:05:40,734 --> 01:05:50,037
[SPEAKER_00]: through today, they have been, in our view, in our team's view, mischaracterized as an attempt to shortchange our teachers.

575
01:05:50,537 --> 01:06:02,601
[SPEAKER_00]: And I sincerely regret that that is the impression that has been made, but it is, in my view, disconnected from both what we have done at the bargaining table as well as what our intentions have been.

576
01:06:04,502 --> 01:06:05,562
[SPEAKER_00]: And if we go to the next slide.

577
01:06:07,324 --> 01:06:10,246
[SPEAKER_00]: As I said, the 18% proposal was an initial proposal.

578
01:06:10,946 --> 01:06:21,772
[SPEAKER_00]: And as we said in our statement last week, the current divide is between a 7.25% proposal that the district has made and a 10% proposal that is on the table from the union.

579
01:06:22,612 --> 01:06:30,717
[SPEAKER_00]: The 7.25% proposal does not include that supplemental pay made possible through the COVID-related grants.

580
01:06:31,297 --> 01:06:37,305
[SPEAKER_00]: that we are attempting and have been attempting for several months to provide to our teachers.

581
01:06:38,675 --> 01:06:49,503
[SPEAKER_00]: If factored in cumulatively, that would have the real feel of approximately 9.1% increase over a three-year period for all teachers.

582
01:06:49,703 --> 01:07:08,276
[SPEAKER_00]: It would be the 7.25% divided by 2.5, 2.25, 2.5, and the $1,000 per teacher per year for three years, with, again, that supplemental pay not being incorporated into the base for the reasons that I referenced earlier with respect to the city's capacity.

583
01:07:10,035 --> 01:07:15,237
[SPEAKER_00]: On June 6, the union made a presentation before you, similar to what I'm doing this evening.

584
01:07:15,297 --> 01:07:19,658
[SPEAKER_00]: I believe that was the date that I asked you not to make me do this publicly.

585
01:07:19,698 --> 01:07:21,438
[SPEAKER_00]: And that didn't work out.

586
01:07:21,458 --> 01:07:22,979
[SPEAKER_00]: So now I'm doing this publicly.

587
01:07:23,939 --> 01:07:27,020
[SPEAKER_00]: And in that presentation, the union presented an analysis.

588
01:07:27,080 --> 01:07:28,020
[SPEAKER_00]: If we could go to the next slide.

589
01:07:28,560 --> 01:07:34,342
[SPEAKER_00]: The union presented an analysis that we could absorb as a district in our operating budget

590
01:07:34,815 --> 01:07:36,896
[SPEAKER_00]: a 2.25% increase.

591
01:07:37,576 --> 01:07:52,621
[SPEAKER_00]: Now, again, as I said before, we had budgeted 2%, and frankly, the difference between 2% and 2 1⁄4 when we're dealing with a $69 million budget is relative, I would say.

592
01:07:53,921 --> 01:07:57,663
[SPEAKER_00]: It's not, frankly, an analysis that the district deeply disagrees with.

593
01:07:58,263 --> 01:07:59,783
[SPEAKER_00]: As I said, right now, our proposal is 2 1⁄2, 2 1⁄4, 2 1⁄2.

594
01:08:02,352 --> 01:08:08,794
[SPEAKER_00]: So to be clear, we do not disagree with the MTA's analysis of our operating budget capacity.

595
01:08:09,775 --> 01:08:26,021
[SPEAKER_00]: Where we do disagree and where we think the facts do not support the arguments that were made on June 6th is the idea that the ESSER money, meaning the temporary grants allocated to the district for purposes of responding to the COVID-19 pandemic,

596
01:08:26,738 --> 01:08:34,200
[SPEAKER_00]: can be used to somehow bridge a gap between this contract and some future date where there is additional revenue.

597
01:08:35,660 --> 01:08:51,244
[SPEAKER_00]: We disagree with that both because from a regulatory perspective, the guidance that we have received from the state and federal government would indicate that this would be an impermissible use of that funding, but also because it would create a structural deficit that may or may not be filled.

598
01:08:52,386 --> 01:08:56,651
[SPEAKER_00]: Now, to be clear, there are different ways in which that structural deficit could be confronted.

599
01:08:57,572 --> 01:09:00,415
[SPEAKER_00]: The taxes in the community could be raised.

600
01:09:00,655 --> 01:09:10,707
[SPEAKER_00]: That could certainly raise sufficient revenue and expand the capacity such that an agreement similar to what the union is proposing could be a viable one in the future.

601
01:09:11,735 --> 01:09:24,822
[SPEAKER_00]: But to that argument, I would say that I think it's a disservice to the community to enter into a contract that we know we can't afford and then tell the members of the community that we should raise their taxes in order to fund the agreement.

602
01:09:25,542 --> 01:09:26,863
[SPEAKER_00]: That's backwards, frankly.

603
01:09:27,083 --> 01:09:38,009
[SPEAKER_00]: And I would say, and again, I try not to reference this too often, but having sat in a chair very similar to yours, I can tell you that it is not an argument that a community typically responds well to.

604
01:09:38,029 --> 01:09:39,450
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think understandably so.

605
01:09:40,350 --> 01:09:50,653
[SPEAKER_00]: The other way in which that structural deficit could be confronted would be if there was additional revenue that came in from the state through increased allocation of Chapter 70.

606
01:09:51,413 --> 01:09:58,895
[SPEAKER_00]: And as I take the union's presentation from that night, I believe that is what they are essentially predicting.

607
01:09:59,596 --> 01:10:02,677
[SPEAKER_00]: And to be clear, they may be right about that.

608
01:10:03,437 --> 01:10:07,038
[SPEAKER_00]: But similar to how it would be out of sequence to

609
01:10:08,729 --> 01:10:15,636
[SPEAKER_00]: enter into an agreement that we know we don't have the capacity for locally, and then tell residents that they have to fund it.

610
01:10:16,016 --> 01:10:28,309
[SPEAKER_00]: It would also seem unorthodox, at best, to enter into an agreement that we don't know with certainty is going to be funded by way of those state revenues.

611
01:10:29,210 --> 01:10:35,396
[SPEAKER_00]: There is certainly the case that the state has committed in various ways to increase its chapter funding allocation.

612
01:10:35,776 --> 01:10:43,584
[SPEAKER_00]: But as those of you who were here when the Student Opportunity Act passed, Medford is not necessarily a principal beneficiary of those increased revenues.

613
01:10:44,065 --> 01:10:46,828
[SPEAKER_00]: And in addition to that, as I said at the beginning of the presentation,

614
01:10:48,038 --> 01:10:51,681
[SPEAKER_00]: Our budget is comprised primarily of a local contribution.

615
01:10:52,161 --> 01:11:05,252
[SPEAKER_00]: So an increase in Chapter 70 funding does not benefit the Medford community in a way that that analysis might carry more water in other communities that benefit more from the state's Chapter 70 formula.

616
01:11:06,253 --> 01:11:10,837
[SPEAKER_00]: So to sum up, if we go back just one slide, Dr. Cushing, thanks.

617
01:11:14,087 --> 01:11:26,861
[SPEAKER_00]: If we could summarize this disagreement, I hope one that we can have respectfully, it is the question of whether temporary grant funding can be used to increase base pay.

618
01:11:27,830 --> 01:11:32,813
[SPEAKER_00]: It is the district's position that it both cannot be and that it should not be.

619
01:11:33,574 --> 01:11:40,478
[SPEAKER_00]: But that is not to say that we don't have a responsibility to find a way to fund a competitive increase.

620
01:11:41,039 --> 01:11:41,439
[SPEAKER_00]: We do.

621
01:11:42,200 --> 01:11:49,424
[SPEAKER_00]: We do have that responsibility, which is why we have put on the table a seven and a quarter percent increase over three years.

622
01:11:50,045 --> 01:11:55,508
[SPEAKER_00]: And then in addition to that, supplemented each teacher's pay with $1,000 per person per year

623
01:11:58,791 --> 01:12:00,292
[SPEAKER_00]: through the COVID-related grants.

624
01:12:01,053 --> 01:12:06,037
[SPEAKER_00]: On this slide, you can see these are all of the wage proposals that the district has made.

625
01:12:08,109 --> 01:12:21,119
[SPEAKER_00]: And again, I think that it is certainly the case that every teacher, every community member has a right, as the union does, to say this is insufficient.

626
01:12:21,579 --> 01:12:23,321
[SPEAKER_00]: And we're just not going to accept that.

627
01:12:24,481 --> 01:12:30,086
[SPEAKER_00]: I think it is our professional responsibility and sort of common sense would say that we have to respect that.

628
01:12:30,646 --> 01:12:42,473
[SPEAKER_00]: But I do believe that if we look at these numbers in this context, the suggestion that somehow this is an intentional ploy by the district to demonstrate disrespect, I think is an untenable position.

629
01:12:42,953 --> 01:12:58,063
[SPEAKER_00]: And I would ask members of the community, as well as people in the organization, to make their own judgment about that as to exactly what intent or what motive the district would have to try to insult the people that are spending,

630
01:12:59,223 --> 01:13:03,265
[SPEAKER_00]: hours every day trying to move the children of this community forward in their lives.

631
01:13:04,365 --> 01:13:05,826
[SPEAKER_00]: I don't know why we would want to do that.

632
01:13:06,366 --> 01:13:15,469
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think if we can't spell out our rationale, then perhaps there's a factual problem with that position.

633
01:13:16,529 --> 01:13:20,951
[SPEAKER_00]: At the bottom here, just to make clear, these increases that we're proposing

634
01:13:21,820 --> 01:13:36,265
[SPEAKER_00]: The 7.25% cost of living adjustment that would be incorporated into the base over three years, which exceeds the amounts for the previous three collective bargaining agreements in Medford, as well as the $1,000 supplemental pay per person per year.

635
01:13:37,106 --> 01:13:43,168
[SPEAKER_00]: In addition to that, the district has proposed, and in some cases the district actually did propose,

636
01:13:43,689 --> 01:13:56,420
[SPEAKER_00]: increasing compensation with respect to missed prep periods, with additional classes that are being taught, as well as longevity payments, which we were happy to offer counterproposals on.

637
01:13:57,021 --> 01:14:01,685
[SPEAKER_00]: So again, why is it that we feel as though we now have to make this information public?

638
01:14:03,700 --> 01:14:12,302
[SPEAKER_00]: because the rhetoric and the threat of job actions have gotten to a point where we are concerned that it could be disruptive to the organization.

639
01:14:12,922 --> 01:14:23,605
[SPEAKER_00]: And it is our hope that through the use of the state mediator, we will increase the chances that we can get to an amicable resolution as quickly as possible.

640
01:14:24,525 --> 01:14:27,346
[SPEAKER_00]: A couple of more slides, and then I'll be happy to take questions.

641
01:14:28,406 --> 01:14:31,327
[SPEAKER_00]: To sum up, with respect to the inflation argument,

642
01:14:33,456 --> 01:14:37,000
[SPEAKER_00]: Everyone in this room is being affected by inflation.

643
01:14:37,721 --> 01:14:41,806
[SPEAKER_00]: And certainly, I don't mean to suggest that everyone in every income bracket is affected equally.

644
01:14:42,046 --> 01:14:44,509
[SPEAKER_00]: That's certainly not true.

645
01:14:44,990 --> 01:14:50,977
[SPEAKER_00]: But it is the case that inflation is a real problem, and it's having a real impact on people's lives.

646
01:14:52,418 --> 01:14:59,205
[SPEAKER_00]: The question is, what organizations and at what level of government do we have the capacity to actually fix that?

647
01:14:59,745 --> 01:15:05,251
[SPEAKER_00]: And the reality is the Medford Public Schools lacks the capacity to fix inflation.

648
01:15:06,052 --> 01:15:13,099
[SPEAKER_00]: And it is why we have a responsibility to act within the capacity that we do have.

649
01:15:13,539 --> 01:15:19,442
